    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>38 Queen’s Gardens | Bayswater, W.</placeName>
                    <date>Sep. 22/ 81</date>
                    <salute>Dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Darwin,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I inclose you a circular which tells its own story.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I have long been wanting to make a move of the kind indicated, and have at length taken this step. Remembering the direction of your sympathies in the Jamaica business, I am inclined to hope you will join us.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> At present, as you see, the action taken is altogether private and but a few names have been obtained. When more public action is taken we shall, I have no doubt, present an imposing front.</p>
<p>Truly yours | Herbert Spencer</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The circular has not been found. Spencer hoped to set up an Anti-Aggression League to curb the aggressive tendencies of colonial powers; he had drawn up the circular outlining his plans on 16 June 1881 (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2194.xml">Duncan 1908</ref>, p. 221).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In 1866, Spencer had asked CD to support the Jamaica Committee, which had called for the criminal prosecution of the colonial governor <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1564.xml">Edward John Eyre</ref> for his actions in suppressing an uprising by the ex-slave population of Jamaica (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 14, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5265.xml">letter from Herbert Spencer, 2 November 1866</ref>). CD subscribed £10 to the committee (see <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5281.xml">letter to J. D. Hooker, 20 November [1866]</ref> and n. 8).</note>
           </div>
        
    
        
